data.content:
## What happened

This is a **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls**, so the expression tree construction (or its interpreted execution) throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting or calling explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree representable. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead of `arr.Reverse()`.
